05648nam a22008535i 9781442657250DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172004onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426572507 a10.3138/97814426572502doi  a(DE-B1597)483243  a(OCoLC)1004879875  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aZ116.A2bF88 2004eb 7aLIT0070002bisacsh04a00222204aThe Future of the Page /ced. by Peter Stoicheff, Andrew Taylor. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (330 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Book and Print Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Architectures, Ideologies, and Materials of the Page -- t1. Turning the Page -- t2. Decolonizing the Medieval Page -- t3. Back to the Future – Littorally: Annotating the Historical Page -- t4. Nicholas Jenson and the Form of the Renaissance Printed Page -- t5. Print Culture and Decolonizing the University: Indigenizing the Page: Part 1 -- t6. Print Culture and Decolonizing the University: Indigenizing the Page: Part 2 -- t7. Visible and Invisible Books: Hermetic Images in N-Dimensional Space -- t8. James Joyce’s Ulysses on the Page and on the Screen -- t9. Our Bodies Are Not Final -- t10. The Processual Page: Materiality and Consciousness in Print and Hypertext -- t11. Virtually Human: The Electronic Page, the Archived Body, and Human Identity -- t12. Artist’s Pages: Decolonizing Tactics in ‘Writing Space’ -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe most basic unit of the physical book is the page. It has determined the historical evolution of the book, the types of information communicated, and how the audience accesses that information.Unique and rewarding in both its scope and approach, The Future of the Page is a collection of essays that presents the best of recent critical theory on the history and future of the page and its enormous influence on Western thought and culture. Spanning the centuries between the earliest record of the page and current computerized conceptions of page-like entities, the essays examine the size of the page, its relative dimensions, materials, design, and display of information.The page is broadly defined, allowing the volume to explore topics ranging from medieval manuscripts to non-European alternatives to the page, Algonquin symbolic literacy, and hypertext. This thought-provoking collection will appeal to literary scholars, book historians, graphic designers, and those interested in the impact of evolving print technologies on intellectual and cultural life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBooksxFormatxHistory. 0aLiteracyxHistory. 0aManuscript designxHistory. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh1 aBattiste, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanto, Edison del, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlson, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDagenais, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFindlay, L.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroden, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManguel, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGann, Jerome, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuri, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlights, William W.E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul